<p>Only those who want to go really fast will need a gear much above 100, though gears as high as 250 have been reported for specialist racing. Cyclists who are fit and strong will find that a low gear of around 40 -50 gear-inches is quite adequate for almost all on-road use. Other cyclists may prefer a somewhat lower gear, perhaps around 20 or 30. The lowest feasible non-specialist gear (as of 2005) is around 15. Tricycles can be bought with gears as low as 8, but such low gears are not really suitable for bicycles due to the problems of balancing at very slow speeds.</p>
<p>As a person ages, their necessary low gear may change. Suppose a cyclist at age 40 regularly <a href="/wiki/Bicycle_commuting" title="Bicycle commuting">commutes</a> by bicycle 11 miles each way without doing any other cycling or exercise. He/she might need a low gear of 45 for the 58-mile <a href="/wiki/London_to_Brighton_events" title="London to Brighton events">London to Brighton</a> charity bike ride, with no need to stand on the pedals even over <a href="/wiki/Sussex" title="Sussex">Ditchling Beacon</a>. Twenty years later the same cyclist (then commuting only 5 miles each way) might need a low gear of 27 for the ride. Another five years later the same cyclist (then commuting 7 miles each way) might feel happier with a low gear of 19 for the ride.</p>
<p>Several gear ratio calculators are <a href="#External_links" title="">linked below</a>. Such calculators are more useful if they show the percentage difference between gears as well as the nominal gear ratios. These calculators require the number of teeth on each gear wheel on the bicycle and the diameter of the back wheel. Standard road wheels, labeled 700c are 70 cm in diameter with the tyre; the smaller 650c wheels are 65 cm in diameter. Mountain, cruiser, and most other types of wheel are 26 inches with tyre.</p>
<p>For gain ratios they also need to know the length of the pedal cranks in millimetres (crank lengths are normally some multiple of 2.5 mm). If the bicycle has an enclosed gear system (hub or bottom bracket), then details of these gears are also needed (make and model is enough for some calculators).</p>
<p><a name="Some_examples" id="Some_examples"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Bicycle_gearing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Some examples">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Some examples</span></h2>
<p>The following gear ratios were calculated using a 700c rear wheel. Similar ratios can be obtained for any size wheel by adjusting the size of the chainring and/or the rear sprocket.</p>
<p>It is possible to get almost any combination of chainwheel sizes and cog sizes, but it is much cheaper to use standard combinations.</p>
<p><a name="Short_local_rides" id="Short_local_rides"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Bicycle_gearing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Short local rides">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Short local rides</span></h3>
<p>Scenario: short distances (up to 5 miles/8 km), fairly flat.</p>
<ul>
<li>Use a single speed bicycle with a gear of around 60.</li>
<li>Desired gears: low around 50, high around 70.
<ul>
<li>Use Sturmey-Archer KS close-ratio 3-speed hub to get gears of 53, 59, 67.</li>
<li>Use a Sturmey-Archer FC close-ratio 4-speed hub to get gears of 49, 58, 65, 71.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Desired gears: low around 40, high around 90, step around 15%.
<ul>
<li>Use single chain ring and a 7-cog (14-32) cassette to get gears of 41, 46, 54, 62, 72, 81, 93.</li>
<li>Use a 7-cog (13-30) cassette to get gears of 40, 46, 52, 59, 70, 79, 91.</li>
<li>Use a Shimano Nexus 7-speed hub to get gears of 38, 44, 50, 59, 68, 78, 92.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p><a name="Regular_commuting" id="Regular_commuting"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Bicycle_gearing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Regular commuting">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Regular commuting</span></h3>
<p>Scenario: between 5 and 10 miles each way on working days, plus occasional longer trips.</p>
<ul>
<li>Desired gears: low around 40, high around 90, step around 15%.
<ul>
<li>Use the same 7-speed gears as for the last option re short local rides above.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Desired gears: low around 40, high around 100, step around 15%.
<ul>
<li>Use single chain ring and a 7-cog (12-28) cassette to get gears of 42, 50, 57, 66, 74, 85, 99.</li>
<li>Use an 8-cog (11-28) cassette to get gears of 41, 47, 54, 63, 71, 81, 95, 103.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Desired gears: low around 30, high around 100, step around 15%.
<ul>
<li>Use single chain ring and an 8-cog (11-34) Megarange cassette to get gears of 32, 42, 47, 54, 64, 72, 83, 98. Note that with this cassette there is a big jump (31%) from 32 to 42.</li>
<li>Or eliminate the big jump by using a 9-cog (11-34) cassette to get gears of 32, 36, 42, 47, 54, 64, 72, 83, 98.</li>
<li>Or use two chainrings (30,40) with an 8-cog (11-28) cassette to get high-range gears 45, 51, 60, 68, 77, 90, 98 and low-range gears 29, 34, 39, 45, 51, 58, 68. Note that there are 4 duplicate gears, so there are really only 10 distinct gears.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Desired gears: low around 30, high around 100, step around 8%.
<ul>
<li>Use two chainrings (39,42) with an 8-cog (12-32) cassette to get high-range gears 41, 47, 54, 63, 71, 81, 95 and low-range gears 33, 38, 44, 50, 59, 66, 75. Note that this combination is what is called 'half-step gearing' - the percentage step between chainrings is about half the step between cogs. The two ranges are interlaced to avoid duplicates (there are 14 distinct gears), but achieving an 8% difference requires simultaneous front and rear derailleur changes on every other gear change.</li>
<li>Or use 3 chainrings (28,38,48) with a 9-cog (13-25) close-range cassette to get high-range gears 56, 62, 68, 76, 81, 86, 93, 100 and mid-range gears 41, 45, 49, 54, 60, 64, 68, 73, 79 and low-range gears 30, 33, 36, 40, 45, 47, 50, 54. There are 20 distinct gears out of a nominal 27, but they are not really usable in sequence.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Desired gears: low around 25, high around 100, step around 15%.
<ul>
<li>Use 3 chainrings (28,38,48) with an 8-cog (11-34) Megarange cassette to get high-range gears 50, 57, 65, 77, 87, 100, 119, and mid-range gears 30, 40, 45, 52, 61, 69, 79, 94 and low-range gears 22, 29, 33, 38, 45, 51, 59. This combination has an 'overdrive' of 119 at the top for those strong enough to use it.</li>
<li>Or use 3 chainrings (24,34,42) with an 8-cog Megarange (11-34) cassette to get high-range gears 44, 49, 57, 67, 76, 87, 103 and mid-range gears 27, 35, 40, 46, 54, 61, 71, 84 and low-range gears 19, 25, 28, 32, 38, 43, 50. This combination has a "crawler gear" or "granny gear" of 19 at the bottom for tackling those really steep hills.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p><a name="Touring" id="Touring"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Bicycle_gearing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Touring">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Touring</span></h3>
<p>Scenario: Longer trips of 30 to 60 miles per day, heavily laden.</p>
<ul>
<li>Desired gears: low around 20, high around 100, with plenty of low gears.
<ul>
<li>Use single chainring with Rohloff 14-speed hub (13.5% difference throughout) to get gears: 19, 22, 25, 28, 32, 36, 41, 47, 53, 61, 69, 78, 89, 101.</li>
<li>Or use 3 chainrings (22,32,44) with an 8-cog (12-32) cassette to get high-range gears 42, 50, 57, 66, 74, 85, 99 and mid-range gears 27, 31, 36, 41, 48, 54, 62, 72 and low-range gears 19, 21, 25, 28, 33, 37, 42. There is a lot of overlap between the ranges, so this combination only has 13 distinct gears out of a nominal 24!</li>
<li>Or use three chainrings (22,39,42) with an 8-cog (12-32) cassette to get high-range gears 41, 47, 54, 63, 71, 81, 95 and mid-range gears 33, 38, 44, 50, 59, 66, 75, 88 and low-range gears 19, 21, 25, 28, 33, 37, 42. This combination uses half-step gearing on the high and middle ranges in combination with a much larger jump between the middle ring and the smallest (granny) ring to provide a total of 19 distinct gears, and is known as "half-step plus granny" gearing.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p><a name="Racing" id="Racing"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Bicycle_gearing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Racing">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Racing</span></h3>
<p>Scenario: Speed is important, strength is assumed.</p>
<p>Desired gears: low around 45, high around 125, step around 8%.</p>
<p>A modern <a href="/wiki/Racing_bicycle" title="Racing bicycle">racing bicycle</a> is often equipped with a double-chainring crankset at the front and a 9-speed or 10-speed cassette at the back. Since wheel size is standardized, the gearing system is often described by stating the number of teeth in the chainrings and cogs. For example, the front chainring gearing is denoted "53/39", meaning that it has 53- and 39-tooth chainrings on the crankset. The rear cassette is denoted by its smallest and its largest. For example, a "12-25" means that the smallest has 12 teeth, and the largest has 25 teeth. Nowadays 9- and 10-speed cassettes are commonplace, which make the choice of intermediate gears less important than when there were only 5 cogs available in a cassette. These cassettes typically have a 7% step on the top 6 or 7 gears, and an 11% step on the lower gears.</p>
<p>Except in special circumstances, most professionals use a combination of a 53/39 front gearing. Some <a href="/wiki/Sprinting_specialist_(cycling)" title="Sprinting specialist (cycling)" class="mw-redirect">sprinters</a> like to use a larger chainring at the front, up to 54t or 55t. In some races involving steep climbs, some professionals opt for a triple chainring at the front to accommodate a smaller gear. Recent popularity of the <a href="/wiki/Compact_drivetrain" title="Compact drivetrain" class="mw-redirect">compact drivetrain</a> allows the use of smaller chainrings at the front, usually a 50/34 or 50/36 combination. This allows the use of a double-chainring drivetrain and having the lower gearing needed for the climbs.</p>
<p><a name="Off-road" id="Off-road"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Bicycle_gearing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Off-road">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Off-road</span></h3>
<p>"Alpine gearing" of approximately 15% step is preferred.</p>
<p>Typically cross country mountain bikes will be fitted with a triple crankset, using 22, 32 and 44 tooth chainrings. The rear cassette is usually an 11 to 32. For downhill specific bikes, road type cassettes may be fitted to provide smaller steps between gears, along with cranksets fitted with one or two drive rings and a bash ring, which takes the place of the largest chainring, and is simply a reinforced, toothless ring, designed to protect the smaller two chainrings from impact via logs, rocks, deep ruts, crashes, etc.</p>
<table class="metadata plainlinks ambox mbox-small-left ambox-notice" style="margin: 4px 1em 4px 0; width: 238px; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 88%; line-height: 1.25em;">
